                    .text-left.text-sm.md:text-base.text-sky-900.space-y-2.flex-1
                        .font-semibold No license needed for integrations
                        div
                            | Anything you drive through a temporary layer works on the `b free tier`, no Pro license required for you or your users. That includes:
                        ul.list-disc.pl-5.space-y-1
                            li Custom layers with any number of keys and modifier combos
                            li Click-to-type (clicking a key on the on-screen keyboard sends the keystroke)
                            li Keyboard layout language awareness (Dvorak, QWERTZ, AZERTY, etc.)
                        div
                            | The only restriction is that you are `b not` allowed to replicate Keylume's core paid feature: `b app cheatsheets`. Unless it's only for showing your own app's shortcuts, that is allowed.

        section#footer-text.flex-center.flex-col.pb-20.space-y-12.w-full.max-w-[800px].px-4.text-left
            .w-full
                -md
                    ## Overview

                    Keylume exposes three equivalent interfaces. The CLI and URL scheme are thin wrappers around the same distributed notifications, so they can do the same operations.

                    - **CLI** (`keylume`). Easiest entry point for shell scripts.
                    - **URL scheme** (`keylume://...`). Handy from `open`, AppleScript, Shortcuts, or browsers.
                    - **Distributed notifications** under `com.lowtechguys.Keylume.*`. For in-process control from another Swift or Objective-C app.

                    ---

                    ## Action reference

                    All actions are reachable from every interface. The notification name is the column on the left, prefixed by `com.lowtechguys.Keylume.`; the URL path is `keylume://<verb>`.

                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr><th>Notification</th><th>URL verb</th><th>Purpose</th></tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr><td><code>show</code></td><td><code>show</code></td><td>Show the keyboard, optionally with a temporary layer</td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>hide</code></td><td><code>hide</code></td><td>Hide the keyboard</td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>toggle</code></td><td><code>toggle</code></td><td>Toggle visibility, optionally with a temporary layer</td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>reset</code></td><td><code>reset</code></td><td>Clear the active temporary layer without hiding</td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>store</code></td><td><code>store</code></td><td>Persist a custom layer without showing the keyboard</td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>edit</code></td><td><code>edit</code></td><td>Update individual keys on a stored layer</td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>remove</code></td><td><code>remove</code></td><td>Delete a stored layer</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>

                    Layers can also be moved to and from JSON files via the URL scheme (`keylume://export`, `keylume://import`) or the CLI (`keylume layers export`, `keylume layers import`).

                    ---

                    ## Parameter reference

                    The `show`, `toggle`, `store`, `edit`, and `remove` actions accept the same key/value mapping. Bindings override key labels while the keyboard is visible; the temporary layer clears when the keyboard hides or when `reset` is called.

                    ### Key names

                    Lowercase QWERTY labels: `a`..`z`, `0`..`9`, `esc`, `tab`, `backspace`, `return`, `f1`..`f12`, `up`, `down`, `left`, `right`, and URL-encoded punctuation keys (`-`, `=`, `[`, `]`, `;`, `'`, `,`, `.`, `/`, `\`).

                    ### Value formats

                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr><th>Format</th><th>Example</th><th>Result</th></tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr><td>plaintext</td><td><code>Save</code></td><td>Text label</td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>s:name</code></td><td><code>s:arrowtriangle.up</code></td><td>SF Symbol</td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>a:bundleID</code></td><td><code>a:com.apple.Safari</code></td><td>App icon</td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>symtext:name|text</code></td><td><code>symtext:magnifyingglass|Find</code></td><td>SF Symbol with a caption below it</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>

                    ### Layer parameters

                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr><th>Key</th><th>Value</th><th>Effect</th></tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr><td><code>fill</code></td><td><code>visible</code>, <code>dim</code>, <code>blank</code></td><td>How keys without a binding look: normal, faintly dimmed, or hidden</td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>blank</code></td><td><code>1</code></td><td>Hide keys without a binding <em>(legacy alias for <code>fill=blank</code>)</em></td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>dimBlankModifierKeys</code></td><td><code>1</code> or <code>0</code></td><td>Also apply <code>fill=dim</code> or <code>fill=blank</code> to non-bindable keys (shift, ctrl, option, cmd, fn). Overrides the user's setting for this layer.</td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>x:y</code></td><td><code>X:Y</code></td><td>Exact screen coordinates <em>(takes priority over <code>position</code>)</em></td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>width</code></td><td>pixels</td><td>Set keyboard width <em>(minimum: <code>500</code>)</em></td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>position</code></td><td>named position</td><td><code>bottom</code>, <code>top</code>, <code>left</code>, <code>right</code>, <code>center</code>, <code>topLeft</code>, <code>topRight</code>, <code>bottomLeft</code>, <code>bottomRight</code></td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>offset</code></td><td><code>X:Y</code> or single value</td><td>Offset or padding for the computed <code>position</code></td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>screen</code></td><td>ID or name</td><td><code>CGDirectDisplayID</code> (number) or a fuzzy name (e.g. <code>dell</code>, <code>built-in</code>). Defaults to the screen with the cursor.</td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>hideAfterMS</code></td><td>milliseconds</td><td>Auto-hide the keyboard after this delay</td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>fadeOutMS</code></td><td>milliseconds</td><td>Fade-out duration before hiding (default: 500)</td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>theme</code></td><td>name</td><td>Apply a saved theme by name (fuzzy match) while the keyboard is shown; reverts when it hides</td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>persist</code></td><td><code>1</code></td><td>Save the layer as a permanent custom layer <em>(requires <code>modifiers</code> or <code>app</code>)</em></td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>modifiers</code></td><td>dash-separated</td><td>Modifier combo that activates the persisted layer (e.g. <code>rcmd-rshift</code>). Possible values: <code>fn</code>, <code>lshift</code>, <code>rshift</code>, <code>lctrl</code>, <code>rctrl</code>, <code>lopt</code>, <code>ropt</code>, <code>lcmd</code>, <code>rcmd</code>, <code>hyper</code></td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>name</code></td><td>text</td><td>Display name for the persisted layer <em>(defaults to <code>modifiers</code> string)</em></td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>app</code></td><td>bundle ID</td><td>Scope the layer to one app. Pair with <code>modifiers</code>, or omit <code>modifiers</code> for the app's base (no-modifier) layer.</td></tr>
                            <tr><td><code>holdDelay</code></td><td>seconds</td><td>Per-app hold-to-summon delay. Requires <code>app</code>. Stored alongside the app's layers.</td></tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>

                    ---

                    ## Command-line interface

                    Keylume ships with a `keylume` CLI. Install it from the menu bar menu, which symlinks it to `~/.local/bin/keylume`. Run `keylume --help` or `keylume <command> --help` for the full option list.

                    ### Visibility

                    ```bash
                    keylume show
                    keylume hide
                    keylume toggle
                    keylume layers reset       # clear any active temporary layer
                    ```

                    ### Temporary overlays

                    Pass key bindings to `show` or `toggle` to override key labels while the keyboard is visible. The overlay clears when the keyboard hides or on `keylume layers reset`.

                    ```bash
                    # Bind keys to app icons / symbols / labels
                    keylume show --app q=Safari --app w=Chrome --symbol e=pencil --text m=Mail --blank

                    # Symbol-with-caption per key (a shortcut cheatsheet)
                    keylume show --symtext f="magnifyingglass|Find" --symtext s="square.and.arrow.down|Save" --dim

                    # Positioning, width, auto-hide, themed display
                    keylume show --position bottom --width 800 --hide-after-ms 3000
                    keylume show --theme "Muted"
                    ```

                    `--theme NAME` applies a saved theme (fuzzy-matched) while visible and reverts on hide.

                    ### Custom layers

                    `keylume layers` manages persisted custom layers. A layer can be global (triggered by a modifier combo system-wide) or scoped to one app (only active when that app is frontmost).

                    ```bash
                    # List
                    keylume layers list                          # one-line summary per layer
                    keylume layers list "App Switcher"           # full key dump for one layer
                    keylume layers list --modifiers rcmd
                    keylume layers list --for-app Pixelmator
                    keylume layers list --json                   # raw export schema

                    # Store
                    keylume layers store --modifiers ralt --name "Browsers" \
                        --app s=Safari --app c=Chrome --app f=Firefox

                    # Edit (creates the layer if it doesn't exist)
                    keylume layers edit --modifiers rcmd --app e=Notes
                    keylume layers edit --modifiers rcmd --unset-key e

                    # Remove
                    keylume layers remove --modifiers rcmd
                    ```

                    ### App-scoped layers

                    Add `--for-app APP` to scope a layer to one app. Without `--modifiers` it becomes the app's base layer, summoned by long-pressing the `fn` key while the app is frontmost.

                    ```bash
                    # Modifier-triggered layer that only shows inside Pixelmator
                    keylume layers store --modifiers cmd --for-app Pixelmator --name "Pixelmator" \
                        --symtext c="doc.on.doc|Copy"

                    # Base layer (no modifier), summoned by long-pressing `fn` inside the app
                    keylume layers store --for-app Pixelmator \
                        --symtext b="paintbrush|Brush" --symtext e="eraser|Erase"

                    # Per-app hold-to-summon delay (seconds)
                    keylume layers store --modifiers cmd --for-app Pixelmator --hold-delay 1.5 \
                        --symtext c="doc.on.doc|Copy"
                    ```

                    ### Themes

                    ```bash
                    keylume themes list                          # active theme marked with *
                    keylume themes export                        # all themes to stdout
                    keylume themes export --name "Nord" -f nord.json
                    keylume themes import themes.json            # duplicates renamed (e.g. "Nord 2")
                    ```

                    ### Export and import

                    ```bash
                    keylume layers export                        # all layers to stdout
                    keylume layers export --modifiers rcmd -f layer.json
                    keylume layers import layers.json            # merges into matching layers
                    keylume layers import layers.json --replace  # overwrites matching layers
                    ```

                    Layers with new modifier combos are added either way. Importing without `--replace` merges bindings into existing layers with the same modifier combo (conflicts use the imported value); with `--replace`, the existing layer is overwritten entirely.

                    ### Raw key format

                    For values that don't fit `--app` / `--symbol` / `--text` / `--symtext`, use `-k KEY=VALUE` with the same value syntax as the URL scheme:

                    ```bash
                    keylume layers store --modifiers rcmd \
                        -k q=app:Safari -k e=symbol:pencil -k m=text:Mail -k f="symtext:magnifyingglass|Find"
                    ```

                    Extended prefixes: `app:Name`, `symbol:name`, `text:value`, `symtext:symbol|text`.

                    ### Flag reference

                    - **`--app KEY=APP`**
                        - Bind a key to an app icon.
                        - `APP` is an app name (`Safari`), a path (`/Applications/Google Chrome.app`), or a bundle ID (`com.apple.Safari`).
                        - App names are fuzzy-matched against installed apps. Key names are case-insensitive.
                    - **`--for-app APP`**
                        - Scope the action to one app, so the layer only shows while that app is frontmost.
                        - Works with `store`, `edit`, `remove`, and (paired with `--persist`) `show` or `toggle`.
                        - Without `--modifiers`, creates the app's base layer (no modifier held, summoned by long-pressing the `fn` key).
                    - **`--hold-delay SECONDS`**
                        - How long to hold a modifier in that app before the keyboard is summoned.
                        - Per-app, so it requires `--for-app`.
                        - Defaults: instant for global layers, 1s for app layers.
                    - **`--blank` / `--dim`**
                        - Control how unbound keys appear.
                        - `--blank` hides them. `--dim` keeps them faintly visible as a reference.
                        - Without either, unbound keys show their normal labels.
                    - **`--dim-blank-modifier-keys` / `--no-dim-blank-modifier-keys`**
                        - Also apply the dim or blank effect to non-bindable keys (shift, ctrl, option, cmd, fn).
                    - **`-k KEY=VALUE`**
                        - Raw key binding (see *Raw key format* above).

                    ---

                    ## URL scheme

                    Every URL action is invoked the same way:

                    ```bash
                    open -g "keylume://<verb>?<params>"
                    ```

                    The `-g` flag keeps the calling app focused. Parameters are URL-encoded query string keys. The supported verbs are listed in the [Action reference](#action-reference); parameters are listed in the [Parameter reference](#parameter-reference).

                    ```bash
                    # Minimal show / hide / toggle
                    open -g keylume://show
                    open -g keylume://hide
                    open -g keylume://toggle
                    open -g keylume://reset

                    # show with a temporary navigation layer
                    open -g "keylume://show?y=s:arrow.left.to.line&u=s:arrow.up&h=s:arrow.left&j=s:arrow.down&k=s:arrow.right&i=s:arrow.right.to.line&blank=1"

                    # Persist an rcmd app switcher
                    open -g "keylume://store?q=a:com.apple.Safari&w=a:com.apple.mail&modifiers=rcmd&name=App%20Switcher"

                    # Update or remove one key
                    open -g "keylume://edit?modifiers=rcmd&e=a:com.apple.Notes"
                    open -g "keylume://edit?modifiers=rcmd&q=-"

                    # Remove a layer
                    open -g "keylume://remove?modifiers=rcmd"

                    # Export / import layers
                    open -g "keylume://export?file=/tmp/layers.json"
                    open -g "keylume://export?file=/tmp/layers.json&modifiers=rcmd"
                    open -g "keylume://import?file=/tmp/layers.json"
                    open -g "keylume://import?file=/tmp/layers.json&replace=1"
                    ```

                    Set a key's value to `-` (as in the `edit` example above) to remove that binding.

                    ---

                    ## Distributed notifications

                    Post to `DistributedNotificationCenter.default()`. The notification name is `com.lowtechguys.Keylume.<action>`; parameters go in `userInfo` as a `[String: String]` dictionary using the same keys and values as the URL scheme.

                    ```swift
                    DistributedNotificationCenter.default().post(
                        name: .init("com.lowtechguys.Keylume.show"),
                        object: nil,
                        userInfo: [
                            "y": "s:arrow.left.to.line",
                            "u": "s:arrow.up",
                            "h": "s:arrow.left",
                            "j": "s:arrow.down",
                            "k": "s:arrow.right",
                            "i": "s:arrow.right.to.line",
                            "blank": "1",
                        ]
                    )
                    ```

                    ### `Notification.Name` extension

                    A convenience extension covering every action:

                    ```swift
                    extension Notification.Name {
                        static let keylumeShow    = Notification.Name("com.lowtechguys.Keylume.show")
                        static let keylumeHide    = Notification.Name("com.lowtechguys.Keylume.hide")
                        static let keylumeToggle  = Notification.Name("com.lowtechguys.Keylume.toggle")
                        static let keylumeReset   = Notification.Name("com.lowtechguys.Keylume.reset")
                        static let keylumeStore   = Notification.Name("com.lowtechguys.Keylume.store")
                        static let keylumeRemove  = Notification.Name("com.lowtechguys.Keylume.remove")
                        static let keylumeEdit    = Notification.Name("com.lowtechguys.Keylume.edit")
                    }
                    ```

                    ---

                    ## Examples

                    ### Temporary navigation layer

                    A throwaway overlay that relabels six keys as vim-style arrows. The bindings clear when the keyboard hides.

                    ![Navigation layer](https://files.lowtechguys.com/keylume-hyper-navigation-layer.png)

                    ```bash
                    keylume show --blank \
                        --symbol y=arrow.left.to.line \
                        --symbol u=arrow.up \
                        --symbol h=arrow.left \
                        --symbol j=arrow.down \
                        --symbol k=arrow.right \
                        --symbol i=arrow.right.to.line
                    ```

                    Equivalent URL:

                    ```bash
                    open -g "keylume://show?y=s:arrow.left.to.line&u=s:arrow.up&h=s:arrow.left&j=s:arrow.down&k=s:arrow.right&i=s:arrow.right.to.line&blank=1"
                    ```

                    ### Persisted app switcher

                    A permanent layer triggered by holding right-cmd. Keys show app icons; pressing one switches to that app.

                    ![Persisted rcmd app switcher layer](https://files.lowtechguys.com/keylume-rcmd-app-switcher-layer.png)

                    ```bash
                    keylume layers store --modifiers rcmd --name "App Switcher" \
                        --app q=Safari --app w=Mail --app e=Notes
                    ```

                    Equivalent URL:

                    ```bash
                    open -g "keylume://store?modifiers=rcmd&name=App%20Switcher&q=a:com.apple.Safari&w=a:com.apple.mail&e=a:com.apple.Notes"
                    ```

                    ### App-scoped layer

                    A layer that only shows while Pixelmator is frontmost, triggered by holding cmd:

                    ```bash
                    keylume layers store --modifiers cmd --for-app Pixelmator --name "Pixelmator" \
                        --symtext c="doc.on.doc|Copy" --symtext v="doc.on.clipboard|Paste"
                    ```

                    ---

                    ## Layer JSON format

                    Layer exports are a JSON array. Each layer carries the same key value syntax as the URL scheme.

                    ```json
                    [
                      {
                        "name": "App Switcher",
                        "modifiers": "rcmd",
                        "enabled": true,
                        "keys": {
                          "q": "a:com.apple.Safari",
                          "w": "s:pencil",
                          "e": "Mail"
                        }
                      }
                    ]
                    ```

                    On import, layers with new modifier combos are always added. Layers with a matching modifier combo are merged by default (conflicts use the imported value); pass `replace=1` (URL / notification) or `--replace` (CLI) to overwrite the existing layer entirely.

